<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Walk Through The Mines of Moria, 2<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8714'>Xanthix "Xanthix" Xanthix</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8714&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 5, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Here I am with another look at some cards from the Mines of Moria expansion. The feedback from my first article suggests that people want some in-depth ideas. Well, I agree, and I&#39;d like to take an in-depth look at some cards and strategies that might be hot when Mines of Moria hits.<br>
<br>
WHO LET THE BALROG OUT?<br>
<br>
First of all, let me correct some of what I said about the Balrog. I said that it was too costly to run with a swarm, and that it&#39;s no fun having him discarded when the party stops at site 5. But as reviewers point out, there are cards like Power and Terror and Troubled Mountains to help play it, and the real way to play the Balrog is to play all your minions at site 4, and then drop the bomb at site 5. Either your opponent stops at 4 from fear *and* at 5 from the Balrog, or they face 8 Goblins and the Flame of Udûn all at once. Nice.<br>
<br>
DWARVEN DEMOLITION TEAM<br>
<br>
In this article, I&#39;d like to take an in-depth look at some new Dwarven cards, and how they work with existing cards. I&#39;ll also hypothesize about a new decktype possible with MoM. First, the dwarves. Let me summarize a few Dwarven cards:<br>
<br>
Beneath the Mountains:<br>
  Condition: discard 3 cards from your deck to play a discarded weapon<br>
Glóin, Friend to Thorin<br>
  5/3 Dwarf, Strength +1 for each Dwarf tale (limit +4)<br>
Hand Axe:<br>
  Secondary +1 strength hand weapon that you can discard for +1 archery<br>
Make Light of Burdens<br>
  Condition: discard 3 cards from your deck to discard a shadow condition on a Dwarf<br>
Realm of Dwarrowdelf<br>
  Condition: discard 3 cards from your deck to make a Dwarf strength +1, damage +1<br>
<br>
In the first set we saw lots of Dwarf cards that dug into the deck to draw or discard cards. Now they&#39;re digging even more! All of these cards have great effects: strength, vitality, and pseudo-archery. But are these cards worth their cost?<br>
<br>
First, lets look at the benefits of these cards. Start with a random Dwarf, probably a 4/2 or 5/3. Add a Dwarven Axe, Hand Axe, Dwarven Bracers, and Endurance of Dwarves, resulting in +4/+1. Now you have a 10/4, or maybe a 14/4 if you&#39;re using Frór or Glóin and the conditions are right (pun intended). Now that your Dwarves&#39; strengths are higher, existing cards like Lord of Moria (all Dwarves damage +1) are usable. The abundance of cheap pump cards (Axe Strike, Cleaving Blow, ...) that add to strength and damage mean that your Dwarves should be able to stand up to any minions, and hew down Cave Trolls and Witch Kings with mighty blows of their axes.<br>
<br>
But what about the costs? Most of these cards are cheap in twilight cost, but require Dwarf exertions or deck discards, and you need a lot more cards to power up a Dwarf than Aragorn. For exertions, there&#39;s actually a lot of healing. Still Draws Breath heals a Dwarf each time they win a skirmish, and MoM&#39;s Till Durin Wakes Again heals Dwarves every time they move underground. Dwarven Heart might be good at site 7 or 8 also.<br>
<br>
As for discarding cards from your deck, that&#39;s a real liability. If you use Realm of Dwarrowdelf to its maximum, you&#39;ve got a +3 str +3 damage Dwarf, but at the cost of discarding a fifth of your deck. Perhaps this represents the Dwarves getting greedy and digging too far too fast? At any rate, it&#39;s dangerous to throw away cards you may want to draw later. But I think that this liability can be turned into an asset. How can discarding cards be an advantage? If you use the discard pile as a resource, that&#39;s how! And how can you do that?<br>
<br>
MORIA RECURSION<br>
<br>
So the Dwarves can do great things, but at the cost of discarding most of your deck? Well, I think the way to make up for that is also in the MoM expansion. A big theme in Moria is recursion - of minions and weapons especially. Relics of Moria, Goblin Scavengers, They Are Coming, Foul Things, Host of Thousands, and the rare Balrog all let you play cards from the discard pile. I think we can pair up the Dwarves with some Moria recursion to make an interesting new decktype. With this deck, the goal would be to dump all your shadow creatures and weapons into the discard pile, and only draw Dwarf cards and Moria events. You can play all the Dwarf cards, dump the minions, and then play them from the discard pile, using shadow events and conditions. It&#39;s perfect if you can set it up - it&#39;s like the entire discard pile is your Goblin Swarms stack! And with the first set&#39;s Dwarf cards that manipulate the top of the deck (Wealth of Moria is perfect for this), I think this is pretty achievable.<br>
<br>
If it worked well, this deck would have great synergy. Your Dwarfs get buff while you dump more minions into the Goblin breeding pit. I really think the decktype could take off. Everyone&#39;s going to be playing the new Dwarf cards and trying out new things with Moria, like archery and tentacles and Balrog toys, but how many people will put 2 and 2 together? Okay, maybe everyone will - but if you do it first you get to name the decktype. :)<br>
<br>
<br>
Well, hopefully this issue has taken a more in-depth look at some of the card strategies and combos that await us in he Mines. Again, please leave feedback, so I know if I should write a third installment or go back to playing Pokemon. :) Remember, whether my predictions are right or wrong, the Mines hold surprises for everyone!<br>
